The Hora is a Jewish tradition where the newlyweds sit on chairs and are lifted in the air. It's REALLY fun😬Family and friends dance in circles as they cheer and sing for the couple as they hold one end of a napkin or a handkerchief that signifies their union🫶​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
As someone who wove a lot of mixed rituals into their wedding ceremony + reception (my husband is Jewish) I am in FULL SUPPORT of incorporating rituals that not only reflect your relationship, but where you come from. This can mean childhood memories, religion, special places, symbolic foods and the list goes on. Sometimes I worry that the industry puts too much emphasis on aesthetics + trends causing couples steer away from the sacred details and rituals that matter most. I promise you that we will help you remain true to your vision as your wedding planning unfolds. XO​​​​​​​​

This image reminds me of my film days✨Fun fact about me: I started developing film in the darkroom in 8th grade. I will never forget the smell, the red light, the way it felt to watch my images develop in that quiet, safe place. Let's be real...middle school is awkward. I LOVED my escape to the darkroom. I continued through high school and merged digital photography into the mix in college. I studied abroad in Southern France in 2006 when there happened to be tons of protests in the French education system which allowed moi to travel all over Europe with my backpack and 📷 What a dream 🫠 At that time I was so passionate about it but never thought it would become my career just a few years later. I am so grateful that I found that darkroom peaceful and special as an innocent 13 year old girl. It set the tone for so much more than I could have imagined at that time :) I went on to get a double major from UC Santa Barbara in Global Studies/International Relations and Women’s Studies. I graduated in June of 2007, and began shooting weddings in Santa Barbara by August of that summer while waiting tables on off nights to make ends meet. My little hobby turned into a big hobby after college. From there it became a job with a restaurant side hustle, and from there it grew into a robust career as a photographer, entrepreneur and boss. You get to write your own story and mine is always a reminder to keep my own mind open for the future 🙏💫💜

I photographed this Yosemite elopement when I was 25 weeks pregnant with Raya. I’ll never forget it. My husband carried my gear in a backpack (along with ALL the pregnancy snacks). 

I felt so alive witnessing some of the most majestic nature in the world while moving my body, growing life and documenting a remarkable love story. It was a marvelous day on many levels. 

For me, this story is a reminder that so many emotional experiences can exist at once when we are grounded and tuned in. I am calling in more of those natural highs in 2023. They’re all rooted in being present and grateful and I can’t think of a better way to be💖

Going from wedding season to the holidays always has me extra introspective in January and I absolutely love it 🥲 I even tell my husband “no plans in Jan!” ​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
Some of you might wonder why I mix Kreate Photography content with my education branch, the Kreate Collective. The reason is because they go hand in hand. Although a large percentage of my following are past and prospective clients, there are also thousands that are creatives and photographers viewing my content. ​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
At this point in my career, it’s part of my greater mission to share what I’ve learned on this long and layered journey with others. Part of my creative process is recharging. The full stop kind of recharge. The “my gear is sent away to canon being cleaned I can’t even book a shoot recharge.” 👏​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
It’s how I’ve avoided boring, repetitive work and continued to show 10000% for my business, and my health and relationships. ​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
Each January, I change the aesthetics of my office just a bit, whether it’s painting an accent wall, having a living mood board, adding a new oil to my diffuser selection, and sometimes it’s in the form or art or reminders. ​​
​​​​​​​​
I’ve got some massive goals for 2023. I’m excited and a little bit scared, to be honest. My motivation can be all consuming sometimes. That’s why being in alignment and taking care of myself has to ALWAYS come first and the rest can follow in a healthy way. ​​​​​​​​
​​​​​​​​
Here is my self care wheel that I’m adding to my office gallery wall for a daily reminder of what’s important and what to check myself on🙏I’m a visual person and can’t wait to see this in a beautiful frame above my desk!!! 🔥🙌🌈

Ready to capture that 'We said yes!' magic? 💍✨ Here are 5 engagement photo prep tips to slay the camera game and avoid overthinking it! 😎📸⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
1. Trust Your Photographer: Leave the magic in the hands of your talented photographer. If they’re anything like me and my team, they will set the tone, make you feel comfortable, and guide you through the entire session 📷✨ It’s also ok to ask for direction! A good Photograher gives direction, not poses ;) For example: prompts to help you relax, movement, walking to distract you and get you in the moment. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
2. Location Love: Scout out a dreamy backdrop that reflects your unique love story. Think romantic parks, urban vibes, or even your favorite cozy coffee shop! 🌸☕ Again ask your photographer for location support too! ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
3. Wardrobe Wins: Dress to impress! Coordinate outfits that complement each other's style and suit the location. Embrace your fabulous fashion sense and let your personalities shine! 👗👔 ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
4. PDA Bay-beee: Don't be afraid to show some PDA (Public Display of Affection)! Be ready to snuggle, laugh, and look at each other a lot. If you’re shy or more private, prepare yourself for this piece as it is a real factor to check in with yourself about! 💑💕 I’ve been photographing couples making out since 2008 so I can assure you you’re in good hands 🫶⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
5. Props & Layers: Add a touch of fun with props and layers! From a cute knit blanket to sit on at the beach, a bottle of your favorite bubbles (best prop ever 😆) or sunglasses…these little things can add more personality to your shoot. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
😍❤️

Some might say it’s eccentric? I say it’s design brilliance. Be bold, be you, let your wedding be a reflection of who you are not what’s trending ✌️

I was very young when I began shooting weddings, it was 2008, I was 22 and right out of college. By 2010, I was shooting about 20 weddings a year and had an incredible mentor whom I became an associate photographer for. 
 
By 2012, I’d relocated to San Francisco, my business was growing, and in
2013 — I quit my part-time waitressing job and dove into full-time. Although it was terrifying, the work kept flooding in and I was feeling excited. 

The busier I got, the more questionable my work habits became (late-night editing in bed, no client boundaries with communication, continuing to do low-paying or free shoots for “friends” and taking on WAY too much). I was on the verge of burnout and knew something needed to change before the quality of my work declined. 

My make or break moment was when I did these 4 things:

01) began outsourcing and delegating which required systems and strategy 
02) hired my first assistant and editor 
03) sought out a financial advisor to help teach me about money management, pricing for profit, taxes and finial systems 
04) built a meaningful brand from the ground up and invested almost all extra income towards that for one year. 

My method isn’t for everyone. But branding, delegation and outsourcing still (to this day) are the three critical areas photographers need to focus on to go from side hustle to sustainable biz.

The biggest mistake photographers make with brand strategy is that they think branding is a visual tool. Although there are visual elements to any brand (aka your brand identity), the bottom line is that branding is a communication tool. 

Most people think that the main reason to take your branding seriously is to look professional....having a fancy logo, a color palette, fonts, etc. NOW - although incredible design can catch someone’s eye IT CAN ONLY DO SO MUCH! 

Photographers tend to over-identify with their photography style as their “brand” when it’s really a very small part of their brand. 

HERE ARE THE KEY POINTS YOU MUST UNDERSTAND TO STAND OUT & SLAY IN 2024! 

👉01 You need to understand what it is you want to communicate to your audience. You want your ideal clients to feel an immediate, genuine connection to your business.

👉02 Your branding needs to be driven by a core message that allows you to draw in your ideal client and show them that they're in the right place.

👉03 A brand strategy is a long-term plan developed to help your business achieve specific goals. Brand consistency is a key part of your strategy, as it builds brand trust.
